explanation:
- OS_module_prop_t: Need the struct/typedef to see the types of .name and .filename (arrays vs pointers) and whether any members are const-qualified; determines whether OS_ModuleInfo modifies the pointee (it calls memset/strncpy and passes it to another function) and thus if the parameter could/should be const.
- OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl: Require the function prototype (parameter constness) because OS_ModuleInfo passes module_prop into this implementation routine. If that callee expects a non-const pointer or modifies the data, module_prop cannot be const.
- OS_common_record_t: Need the struct definition to determine the type of record->name_entry (char * vs const char *) and whether the source of the strncpy is already const-qualified; this affects whether pointers to those name data should be const.
- OS_module_internal_record_t: Need the struct definition to determine the type of module->file_name (char * vs const char *); affects whether those source strings should be const-qualified.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Need the macro expansion/type returned to know whether the retrieved record/module pointers are const-qualified; the macro may cast or return const pointers which impacts the constness analysis of the source data used by strncpy.
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Need the macro definition to see if it performs any casts or writes (side-effects) to the pointer parameter or otherwise forces a non-const type; it may also affect whether a pointer parameter is intended for input-only vs output.

These symbols provide the type and const-qualification information needed to decide if module_prop and the other pointers involved can/should be declared as pointers to const according to the MISRA guideline.
